<F P=101> Poland </F>
<H3> <TI>   Pol Airs Views on Ministerial Post, Party </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Pol Airs Views on Ministerial Post, Party </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2706141094 Warsaw PAP in English 1331 GMT 27 Jun 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> LD2706141094 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw PAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Warsaw, June 27 -- Industry Minister Marek Pol 
announced on Monday that he will meet with both Prime Minister 
Waldemar Pawlak and leader of the Union of Labour [UP] Ryszard 
Bugaj later in the week. "I realise that I may have to choose: 
Either remain a minister, or a member of the party," said Pol. 
When asked if one can be a member of an opposition 
parliamentary caucus and a minister at the same time, Pol 
replied: "It is virtually impossible." 
  Pol recalled that he voted against the decision of his party 
to join the opposition to the government coalition and that he 
does not represent any specific political grouping in the 
ministry, but finds himself there due to his experience and 
qualifications. 
  The National Council of the Union of Labour decided on 
Sunday 
to switch over to the ranks of the opposition. The direct cause 
behind the decision was, according to Union of Labour leaders, 
the "Strategy for Poland" economic policy presented by Deputy 
Prime Minister and Finance Minister Grzegorz Kolodko which in 
their opinion signals a shift to the right in the government's 
policy. 

</TEXT>

