<H3> <TI>   Robaina Comments on Refugees in Belgian Embassy </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Robaina Comments on Refugees in Belgian Embassy </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2905162394 Havana PRENSA LATINA in Spanish 1438 GMT 29 May 
94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PA2905162394 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana PRENSA LATINA </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Havana, 29 May (PL) -- Cuban Foreign Minister 
Roberto Robaina said pressure and force are not the mechanisms 
to use to leave the country, referring to the more than 100 
Cuban nationals who forced their way into the residence of the 
Belgian ambassador in this capital. 
  Moments before his departure for Cairo, Egypt, Robaina said 
the island's government is holding talks with the Belgian 
Government to find a solution to Saturday's incident but said 
Cuba's position will be the same one it has always maintained. 
  In this regard, Robaina said they must leave the residence, 
because forcing one's way into diplomatic missions "is not the 
way to leave the country, and, therefore, it is up to the 
Belgian authorities, who are aware of the positions we have 
maintained in this regard, to take the proper steps." 
  [Havana PRENSA LATINA in Spanish at 0101 GMT on 29 May 
transmits an 80-word report, datelined Havana, citing Belgian 
Ambassador Paul Vermeirsch, who today told PRENSA LATINA that 
"he has no comment whatsoever on the forcible entry into his 
residence by a group of people whose objectives had not been 
announced." Vermeirsh added that "any report on today's 
incident in that diplomatic mission would be conveyed by the his 
country's Foreign Ministry in Brussels, the Belgian capital."] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

