<H3> <TI>   GRANMA INTERNATIONAL Launching German Edition </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    GRANMA INTERNATIONAL Launching German Edition </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2805231494 Havana PRENSA LATINA in Spanish 2212 GMT 26 May 
94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PA2805231494 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana PRENSA LATINA </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Havana, 26 May (PL) -- The Cuban weekly GRANMA 
INTERNATIONAL will be published in German for distribution in 
Germany, Austria, Switzerland, and The Netherlands to inform 
tourists from those countries who visit the island, the 
newspaper's directors announced here today. 
  GRANMA INTERNATIONAL editorial director Gabriel Molina said, 
at a ceremony during which Edition Zero in German was presented, 
that the event was a day for celebration because a dream has 
come true after four years of hard work. 
  GRANMA's first issue of its monthly edition to 
German-speaking European countries is dedicated to Cuba's 
struggle to maintain its sovereignty and the achievements of its 
revolution despite the disappearance of the Socialist Bloc and 
the intensification of Washington's blockade. 
  Molina noted that the German edition of GRANMA 
INTERNATIONAL, 
the first Latin American publication in that language, will at 
first be issued monthly. Once it is consolidated, it will 
become a weekly publication as are the Spanish, English, French, 
and Portuguese editions. 
  GRANMA was initially published in three foreign languages on 
15 February 1966, later in Portuguese, and now in German. 
  It now it circulates in 76 countries. For the past two years 
it has been printed in Argentina, Mexico, and Brazil. The 
German edition will be printed in Luxembourg so that it will 
reach readers faster. 
  Including the copies printed in various countries, GRANMA's 
publishes over 70,000 copies. 

</TEXT>

