<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   Exercise Prepares for Possible Natural Disasters </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Exercise Prepares for Possible Natural Disasters </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2805231394 Havana PRENSA LATINA in Spanish 0414 GMT 28 May 
94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PA2805231394 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana PRENSA LATINA </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Walfredo Angulo] </F>
  [Excerpts] Havana, 28 May (PL) -- Only 72 hours before the 
beginning of the hurricane season in Cuba, an exercise called 
Meteor 94 has begun throughout the country aimed at implementing 
the various mechanisms needed to confront the forces of nature 
that could hit the island. 
  It is believed that hundreds of thousands of people 
throughout the island will participate in this exercise, which 
is based on the UN plan to prevent catastrophes. [passage 
omitted] 
  The goal of this exercise is to prepare the people and civil 
defense organizations for floods, earthquakes, heavy rains, and 
hurricanes. During the Meteor 94 exercise, the islanders will 
pretend to be bracing for and confronting a very big hurricane. 
  The Cuban specialists have justified this exercise with 
numbers. In the past 200 years, the island has been hit by 90 
hurricanes that have resulted in many dead and wounded and heavy 
material damage. [passage omitted] 
  During the exercise the people will pretend to be bracing 
for 
a hurricane that has been baptized "Claudy." This hurricane 
will follow the same trajectory followed by "Gilbert," a 
hurricane that hit Cuba, Jamaica, the Dominican Republic, Haiti, 
Honduras, Nicaragua, Guatemala, and Mexico's Yucatan Peninsula 
in 1988. [passage omitted] 
  Meteor 94 is designed to alert people to this type of 
catastrophe and update civil defense mechanisms, as well as to 
establish the role of the media in such a situation. The goal 
is to create a safer world as the year 2000 approaches. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

