<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Electoral Developments </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Roundup of Electoral Developments </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2605201794 </F>
<F P=103> PA2605201794 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
BFN 

    [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on developments related to the elections scheduled for 
21 August. 
  In Mexico City, officials from eight of the nine political 
parties have signed an Agreement for Electoral Transparency and 
Fairness. In the agreement, the parties committed to taking 
necessary steps to ensure that all stages of the electoral 
process are carried out within a framework of harmony, mutual 
respect, transparency, security, trust, and credibility. The 
director of the National Action Party (PAN) in Mexico City said: 
"Public funds should not be channeled to any political party." 
(Mexico City XEW Television Network in Spanish 0430 GMT 20 May 
94) 
  Federal District Mayor Manuel Aguilera Gomez has told the 
leaders of the eight political parties who signed the Agreement 
for Electoral Transparency and Fairness that Mexico City will 
not be held "hostage" to conflict caused by political 
differences among the various parties. Aguilera Gomez said: "If 
we want to live in peace, we must adopt a policy of inclusion, 
not exclusion." (Mexico City UNOMASUNO in Spanish 10 May 94 pp 
1, 11) 
  The Chamber of Deputies has elected six new advisers who 
will 
form part of the Federal Electoral Institute's General Council 
in the upcoming 21 August elections. All of the advisers meet 
the legal requirement of not having belonged to or led any 
political party over the past three years. The main duty of 
these advisers will be to oversee the election's transparency 
and honesty. (Mexico City Canal 13 Television Azteca Network in 
Spanish 1300 GMT 25 May 94) 
  PAN candidate Diego Fernandez de Cevallos claims that ever 
since the 11 May debate, attempts to tarnish his image have 
increased. "I have been accused of being an attorney for drug 
traffickers, a member of Opus Dei, and a member of secret 
organizations," Fernandez said. He said there is an attempt to 
undermine his platform in which he places his trust for 
democracy's victory in Mexico. (Mexico City Canal 13 Television 
Azteca Network in Spanish 1300 GMT 25 May 94) 
  PAN candidate Diego Fernandez de Cevallos has spoken out in 
favor of modifying the Federal Labor Law in an effort to 
modernize it without taking back gains made in the area of 
workers rights. He also said there is an urgent need to 
democratize labor unions. He said: "For the sake of protecting 
the workers, we must seek measures that protect jobs and create 
structures that do not hinder the hiring of workers. We know 
that many times false protectionism only leads to unemployment." 
(Mexico City Radio ACIR Network in Spanish 0000 GMT 26 May 94) 
  After a four-hour meeting, members of the Democratic 
Revolutionary Party's (PRD) National Executive Commission 
decided to accept a debate with Carlos Almaga, director of the 
National Voter Registration Office. The PRD will be represented 
by Samuel del Villar, and it was decided that the debate would 
last 53 minutes instead of 45, as had originally been proposed. 
The debate will take place at Federal Electoral Institute 
Headquarters. PRD leader Porfirio Munoz Ledo said: "Del Villar 
has a knowledge of the issues -- legal as well as technical 
knowledge -- and, therefore, we hope he can demonstrate what is 
evident: the fact that enormous errors exist in the electoral 
register." (Mexico City Radio ACIR Network in Spanish 0000 GMT 
26 May 94) 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

