<F P=100> CARIBBEAN </F>
<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   PRC Demands U.S. Lift All Sanctions </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    PRC Demands U.S. Lift All Sanctions </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   FL2805015394 Havana Tele Rebelde and Cuba Vision Networks in 
Spanish 0000 GMT 28 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL2805015394 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana Tele Rebelde and Cuba Vision Networks </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the NTV newscast] </F>
  [Text] The PRC Foreign Ministry has demanded that all U.S. 
sanctions imposed on that country be lifted. The demand was 
made after the United States renewed its most-favored-nation 
trading status with the PRC. The Foreign Ministry underscored 
in a declaration issued in the Chinese capital after Washington 
announced its decision that the renovation will create favorable 
conditions for strengthening and expanding bilateral economic 
and trade relations. Before the Clinton administration's 
announcement on trade with the PRC, U.S. businessmen had warned 
that interrupting trade relations would cost U.S. consumers more 
than $10 billion. Diplomatic sources in Beijing do not rule out 
that the existing ties could be reinforced by a visit by U.S. 
President Clinton to Beijing sometime this year. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

