<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   Robaina Departs for Nonaligned Summit, Qatar </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Robaina Departs for Nonaligned Summit, Qatar </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   FL2905222294 Havana Tele Rebelde and Cuba Vision Networks in 
Spanish 1700 GMT 29 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL2905222294 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana Tele Rebelde and Cuba Vision Networks </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Sunday Supplemental NTV" newscast] </F>
  [Text] A delegation headed by Foreign Minister Roberto 
Robaina has departed for the Nonaligned Movement [NAM] 
ministerial summit in Cairo. Robaina explained the goals of the 
summit, Cuba's position, and his visit to Qatar before departing: 
  [Begin Robaina recording] The goals are not far from the 
aspirations Cuba has always defended regarding the NAM. Since 
Cuba became a member, it has always called for strengthening the 
Movement and its authority in representing the poor of the Earth 
and those who do not have enough resources to allow their 
peoples to live the way they deserve and to attain a voice and 
authority that can be heard in the international arena. 
  These main goals that unite us are to strengthen the NAM and 
to turn the NAM into a strong force at the United Nations and 
other international forums and discussions. I believe in 
turning the NAM into a truly integrated force, not only in terms 
of North-South cooperation but also in terms of South-North 
cooperation. Why not South-South cooperation? All these things 
are part of the very broad agenda which we will discuss in Cairo. 
  I will visit Qatar at the invitation of that country's 
foreign minister, who, as you know, visited Cuba a few months 
ago. The main goal of this trip is to open our diplomatic 
mission in Qatar. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

