<H3> <TI>   Press Report on Border Dispute With Chile Denied </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Press Report on Border Dispute With Chile Denied </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY2705222394 Buenos Aires NOTICIAS ARGENTINAS in Spanish 
0018 GMT 27 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> PY2705222394 </F>
<F P=104>  Buenos Aires NOTICIAS ARGENTINAS </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Buenos Aires, 26 May (NA) -- In connection with a 
Chilean map that shows serious irregularities which was 
published by a Buenos Aires morning newspaper, the Foreign 
Ministry stated today that "there is no border conflict between 
Argentina and Chile." 
  According to Argentine officials, the map was published in 
black and white "without showing the colored areas and without 
the explanatory notes of the original, thus making a serious 
mistake in its interpretation." 
  In a communique, the Foreign Ministry assures that the map 
published with the report was taken "from a chart in the `Atlas 
of Chilean History,' by Osvaldo Silva, published by Editorial 
Universitaria in 1992." 
  The communique says: "The original clearly shows areas on 
the 
map as Argentine territory assigned to Chile. These are the 
territories that were `stripped' from Chile as of 1563 until the 
end of the 19th century when new viceregal jurisdictions and 
border treaties were implemented." 
  It makes clear: "The original map entails no claim by Chile 
to any current Argentine territory." 
  The Foreign Ministry emphasizes that "there is no border 
dispute" between the two countries, and that of the 24 pending 
border issues that remained unresolved until 1991, "22 were 
settled through a bilateral agreement that was signed that year." 
  The two remaining issues, Laguna del Desierto and the 
continental glacier zone, are being considered by the two 
Congresses. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

