<F P=100> Panama </F>
<H3> <TI>   Free Zone To Heed UN Sanctions Against Haiti </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Free Zone To Heed UN Sanctions Against Haiti </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2805220194 Panama City LA ESTRELLA DE PANAMA in Spanish 28 
May 94 p A7 </F>

<F P=103> PA2805220194 </F>
<F P=104>  Panama City LA ESTRELLA DE PANAMA </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Esteban Huertas G.] </F>
  [Text] Galo Pinto, executive director of the Association of 
Colon Free Zone Users, said yesterday that the Colon Free Zone 
"will abide by the commercial sanctions ordered by the UN 
against Haiti." Pinto said that "this Free Zone respects the 
decisions made by the government" in regard to situations that 
affect the democratic development of any country, in this case 
Haiti. 
  Galo Pinto said that "users of the Free Zone are studying 
the 
effects the suspension of commercial exchange will have on that 
Caribbean nation." 
  Meanwhile, a reliable source who requested anonymity said 
that "Haitian businessmen are among the top clients of the Free 
Zone; they invest thousands of balboas to purchase products that 
are later reexported" to that French-speaking nation. 
  According to the spokesperson, "Haiti currently has one of 
the biggest markets in the Caribbean and ranks among the 10 
biggest Free Zone purchasers." 
  For the second time, the Colon Free Zone, third-largest free 
zone in the world after Hong Kong and Singapore, will respect 
the UN decision against Haiti. The UN sanctions on Haiti are 
aimed at restoring democracy in that country and ensure the 
return to the country of ousted President Jean-Bertrand Aristide. 
  The Association of Colon Free Zone Users is currently 
studying the dispositions being implemented by other Latin 
American governments against Haiti. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

