<F P=100> Peru </F>
<H3> <TI>   Guzman Video Helps in Arrest of SL's `No. 2' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Guzman Video Helps in Arrest of SL's `No. 2' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY2805032894 Madrid EFE in Spanish 1509 GMT 27 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> PY2805032894 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] Lima, 27 May (EFE) -- The video showing Shining 
Path [SL] leader Abimael Guzman, which police seized in 1991, 
still is delivering mortal blows to the movement: It has helped 
capture the current Shining Path "No. 2" leader, Felipe Tenorio. 
  In February 1991, police found a videocassette in a Lima 
house supposedly used as Guzman's hideout. In the video, Guzman 
could be seen imitating the dance shown in the film "Zorba, the 
Greek." 
  The video also showed the main Shining Path leaders close to 
Guzman. Among them was Felipe Tenorio Barbaran, aka "Augusto," 
who also was dancing with his chief, "President Gonzalo" as he 
is addressed by his followers. 
  On 26 May, Peruvian police publicly presented Tenorio to the 
country dressed in the striped uniform worn by arrested 
terrorists. Tenorio probably will be sentenced to life 
imprisonment. 
  According to police, "Augusto" was the "No. 2" man in the 
new 
Central Committee of the Peruvian Communist Party, which is the 
real name of the Maoist terrorist group. "Augusto" is second 
only to Oscar Ramirez Durand, aka "Feliciano," who is the 
current Shining Path leader. 
  "Feliciano" has been trying to reorganize the terrorist 
group 
since Abimael Guzman's arrest in Lima on 12 September 1992. 
Guzman was later sentenced to life imprisonment. 
  "Feliciano" has bluntly rejected Guzman's proposal to the 
Peruvian Government calling for a peace accord as well as his 
orders to suspend attacks and murders. [passage omitted] 
  As in Guzman's case, "Augusto" was arrested at a house in 
Los 
Olivos District, Lima, without having the chance to shoot a 
single shot. He had been one of terrorists most wanted by the 
National Counterterrorism Directorate (Dincote). [passage 
omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

