<F P=100> Colombia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Samper, Pastrana Proclaim Victory </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Samper, Pastrana Proclaim Victory </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA3005041294 Madrid EFE in Spanish 0332 GMT 30 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA3005041294 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Santa Fe de Bogota, 29 May (EFE) -- Candidates 
Ernesto Samper and Andres Pastrana proclaimed victory today in 
Colombia's initial presidential elections and both expressed 
their confidence that they will win in the runoff elections on 
19 June. 
  The candidates made brief statements after 95.6 percent of 
the votes were counted and the results announced, giving them a 
wide margin over the remaining 16 candidates. 
  Liberal candidate Samper regretted that he did not win in 
the 
initial elections and thanked the residents of Santa Fe de 
Bogota who gave him a relatively broad margin compared with the 
rest of the country. 
  The liberals expected to garner more votes and the climate, 
although festive, was one of concern at the Orquidea Real Hotel 
where Samper kept abreast of the vote count. 
  The Pastrana supporters, on the other hand, were euphoric in 
the Tequendama Hotel because the slight margin garnered by 
Samper augurs well for them in the runoff elections. 
  Pastrana thanked his family, his supporters, and all of 
those 
who voted for any candidate and invited them to join his 
bandwagon. 
  Candidate Antonio Navarro of the Commitment with Colombia 
movement, who obtained a little over 3.5 percent of the votes, 
said he "was calm because despite all the difficulties that 
existed during the campaign, we obtained a decent and dignified 
vote which leaves us in a position to do well in the future." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

