<DOCNO> FBIS4-32912 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drlat104_o_94023" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-LAT-94-104 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  28 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Colombia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Military Presence Increased </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Military Presence Increased </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2805020994 Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Canal 
A Network in Spanish 0000 GMT 28 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2805020994 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Canal 
A Network </F>

<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Seven O'Clock Newscast"] </F>
  [Text] No elections have ever been so well protected in the 
country. At least, this is what the defense minister, who has 
set up a communications network throughout the country, has 
planned. The government has increased its military presence in 
the country's most conflict-ridden areas to prevent guerrilla 
threats from hampering Sunday's elections. 
  [Begin Defense Minister Rafael Pardo Rueda recording] The 
Armed Forces are present at every municipality seat. 
Approximately 88 percent of the voting sites are covered, also. 
The Armed Forces are present at every location with more than 
three voting sites. This protection of the election process by 
the Public Force has been the most complete in the country's 
history. [end recording] 
  The minister said the Army's presence on the streets of 
Santa 
Fe de Bogota is due to the election process and not to the 
capital's security problems. 
  [Begin Pardo Rueda recording] The Army can cooperate with 
the 
police in the latter's work but cannot replace it. [end 
recording] 
  For election day, a communications system has been set up 
which will make it possible for authorities to act quickly and 
effectively if necessary. 

</TEXT>

