<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   Stand on Occupation of Embassies Reaffirmed </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Stand on Occupation of Embassies Reaffirmed </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2905194494 Havana PRENSA LATINA in Spanish 1858 GMT 29 May 
94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PA2905194494 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana PRENSA LATINA </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Havana, 29 May (PL) -- The Cuban Government today 
reaffirmed its categorical rejection of the illegal entrance to 
diplomatic offices in Havana as a means to abandon the country. 
  A press note issued at noon by the national television 
newscast referred to the forceful entrance by more than 100 
Cubans to the Belgian ambassador's residence on Saturday 
afternoon "to apply pressure tactics in order to leave the 
country." 
  It pointed out that "this new incident is nothing more than 
the result of provocations to commit illegal actions by 
counterrevolutionary stations that transmit from Miami, and 
especially the result of the restrictive policy implemented by 
the U.S. immigration authorities." 
  The United States, the note adds, "continues to obstruct the 
legal procedures of people interested in migrating to that 
country who, after failing several times, resort to illegal 
means, even violent ones, to achieve their goal." 
  The text, which was also aired by the radio stations, says 
that the Cuban Government has not prevented the departure from 
the island of people who complete their procedures legally. 
  Cuban Foreign Minister Roberto Robaina said that the group 
occupying the Belgian diplomatic residence must leave that place 
"because pressure tactics and forceful means are not adequate 
mechanisms to leave Cuba." He pointed out that the island, in 
view of this incident, will maintain its usual position and that 
the Belgian authorities, being aware of the position toward such 
cases, should take the proper measures. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

