<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<H3> <TI>   Cuban Solidarity Group Protests Outside U.S. Embassy </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Cuban Solidarity Group Protests Outside U.S. Embassy </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA3005170794 Mexico City NOTIMEX in Spanish 1527 GMT 30 May 
94 </F>

<F P=103> PA3005170794 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City NOTIMEX </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Mexico City, 30 May (NOTIMEX) -- A group of 35 
youths from the solidarity group Let's Go for Cuba have staged a 
protest in front of the U.S. Embassy because of U.S. Senator 
Robert Torricelli's prescence in Mexico. 
  This Sunday, members of the organization displayed Mexican 
and Cuban flags and placed a coffin with an Uncle Sam dummy that 
would be burned bearing the words "Apply Article 33 (of the 
Constitution) to Torricelli." 
  The protesters explained that they burned the effigy to 
reject the democratic lawmaker's visit. Torricelli is 
well-known for his opposition to the signing of NAFTA as well as 
for promoting a tighter U.S. border and the Cuba Democracy Act 
establishing the commercial blockade against the island. 
  While the police guard remained alert, Jose Carrillo, main 
speaker at the "peaceful and symbolic demonstration," outlined 
the main points of the protest: "To declare Robert Torricelli 
persona non grata," an end of the 33-year-old U.S. blockade 
against Cuba, and the preferential sale of Mexican crude oil to 
the island. 
  Carrillo noted the historical solidarity between Mexico and 
Cuba and said that "to struggle for Cuba is to struggle for 
Mexico, dignity, independence, and sovereignty." He indicated 
that his group sent a letter to the Chamber of Deputies with 
13,000 signatures requesting the shipment "under special 
conditions" of crude oil to Cuba, as well as stating Mexican 
support to end the U.S. blockade against that country. 
  At the end of the protest, Carrillo asserted that in a 
month, 
the solidarity group Let's Go for Cuba will send a third boat 
with hydrocarbons, medicine, and other kinds of aid to Cuba. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

