<F P=106> [From the NTV newscast] </F>
  [Text] South Africa's imminent incorporation into the 
Nonaligned Movement [NAM] and Cuba's election to one of the vice 
presidencies of the summit were two of the main results of the 
meeting for experts which concluded on 30 May, prior to the 
ministerial meeting. Diplomatic sources report that the 
meeting's agenda was approved and that its essential points 
include an analysis of the international political and economic 
situation and of the NAM's role for the immediate future. 
Egyptian President Husni Mubarak will officially open the 11th 
NAM summit on 31 May. The summit will conclude on 3 June. 
  Cuban Foreign Minister Roberto Robaina had a very busy 
agenda 
while the summit was taking place at the Cairo Conference 
Center, meeting several officials including the Arab League 
secretary general and the Zimbabwean, Vietnamese, Iraqi, and 
Burmese foreign ministers on the need to strengthen the NAM and 
the principles that gave birth to the Movement. The common 
denominator at these meetings was to give continuity to the 
positive results the NAM has experienced under Indonesia's 
presidency since the Jakarta summit. 
  Just minutes ago, Robaina met Honduran Foreign Minister 
(Ernesto Rojas), who conveyed a friendly greeting from President 
Reina. (Rojas) announced during the meeting his forthcoming 
visit to Havana in response to Robaina's invitation. 

</TEXT>

