<F P=100> CARIBBEAN </F>
<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   Alarcon Comments on UK Attitude Toward Embargo </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Alarcon Comments on UK Attitude Toward Embargo </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   FL3105224994 Havana Cuba Vision Network in Spanish 0000 GMT 
31 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL3105224994 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana Cuba Vision Network </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the NTV newscast] </F>
  [Text] Ricardo Alarcon, president of the National Assembly 
of the People's Government [ANPP], asserted at the conclusion of 
his visit to the UK that he had perceived an atmosphere of 
friendship towards Cuba in his contact with government 
authorities, parliamentarians, and businessmen. Alarcon headed 
an ANPP delegation integrated by Lidia Tablada, who presides 
over the Friendship with Great Britain group of the ANPP, and 
Osvaldo Martinez, president of the Economic Affairs Commission 
of the ANPP. 
  Upon his return to Cuba, Alarcon commented on the interest 
that the British Parliament expressed towards Cuba. Alarcon's 
visit to Great Britain included meetings with the top leaders of 
the House of Commons and the House of Lords. Alarcon informed 
this newscast that on 27 May, the agenda of the British 
Parliament included British-Cuban relations. 
  [Begin Alarcon recording] There was a very interesting 
debate 
in the parliament regarding relations with Cuba. A government 
minister took part in this debate and very clearly reaffirmed 
Great Britain's policy of continuing and developing economic and 
commercial relations with Cuba. [end recording] 
  Alarcon asserted that he had witnessed, in parliament, Great 
Britain's position with regard to the U.S. blockade against Cuba. 
  [Begin Alarcon recording] In the parliamentary debate that I 
mentioned, MP Arnold, who is a leader of the Conservative Party 
and the one who brought up the issue, and the minister of 
commerce, who replied on behalf of the government, both clearly 
expressed Britain's disagreement with the blockade policy. A 
commitment to noncompliance with the blockade was clear, as was 
the intent to strengthen ties with Cuba. [end recording] 
  Alarcon stated the British minister of commerce will visit 
Cuba in September. 
  The same flight that brought the Cuban delegation back home 
carried Marcelino dos Santos, president of the National Assembly 
of Mozambique, who asserted that he came to learn, profoundly 
and scientifically, about the revolutionary process in Cuba. 

</TEXT>

