<F P=100> Dominican Republic </F>
<F P=101> Haiti </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Bans Malval, Officials From Leaving </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Bans Malval, Officials From Leaving </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA3105193994 Paris AFP in Spanish 1854 GMT 31 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA3105193994 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Port-au-Prince, 31 May (AFP) -- On Tuesday, the 
government of provisional President Emile Jonassaint, which is 
not recognized by the international community, banned members of 
the resigning administration of Prime Minister Robert Malval 
from leaving the national territory. 
  In a communique read over state television, the Ministry of 
Interior and National Defense "informs border posts and those 
concerned of the formal prohibition against leaving the country 
effective immediately for those who have to give explanations on 
their use of public funds." This measure, which also involves 
all high-ranking officials appointed by exiled President 
Jean-Bertrand Aristide or Malval, is aimed at officially 
reviewing the country's accounts. 
  According to observers in Port-au-Prince, however, this 
directive may cause tension between the authorities of the 
administrations of Jonassaint and Malval, who, despite tendering 
his resignation, continues to administer current affairs while 
waiting for President Aristide to appoint a new head of 
government. 
  This measure was adopted "with the legitimate concern to 
guarantee the interests of the public administration and the 
state," the communique said. Former officials must present 
official proof of their handling of affairs at the moment of 
leaving the territory. Some of Malval's ministers are already 
abroad, according to well- placed sources. Following his 
election, Father Aristide ordered the same measure, which was 
denounced at the time as political vengeance. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

