<H3> <TI>   Invasion Rumors Generate Fear, Concern </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Invasion Rumors Generate Fear, Concern </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   FL3105201394 Port-au-Prince Signal FM Radio in French 1300 
GMT 31 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL3105201394 </F>
<F P=104>  Port-au-Prince Signal FM Radio </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] On the night of 30 May, rumors of military 
intervention exacerbated fear and worry among Haitian families; 
rumors that the U.S. military was controlling Mais Gate Airport. 
The rumors appear to have stemmed from a U.S. officer's 
statement on the military invasion of Haiti that was 
misunderstood. 
  A reliable source told Signal FM that a U.S. Army colonel 
said U.S. authorities have decided to invade Haiti and that all 
that remains now is to determine the main targets. This Army 
colonel also said Mais Gate Airport will be one of the main 
targets. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-32967 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drlat105_c_94004" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-LAT-94-105 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  30 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Disagrees With U.S. Cement Exports Decision </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Disagrees With U.S. Cement Exports Decision </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA3105194194 Mexico City Canal 13 Television Azteca Network 
in Spanish 1300 GMT 30 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA3105194194 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City Canal 13 Television Azteca Network 
in Spanish 1300 GMT 30 May 94 </F>

<F P=105> Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Patricia Gutierrez from the "Early Morning" </F>
newscast] 
  [Text] The Mexican Government has expressed its total 
disagreement with the preliminary decision by U.S. authorities 
to apply taxes on Mexican exports of cement clinker and portland 
cement. The U.S. Commerce Department based its decision on the 
argument that Mexican export companies did not provide adequate 
information on Mexico's cement sales to the U.S. market. 
  Commerce Secretary Jaime Serra Puche said that if the final 
decision by the U.S. Government in August turns out to be 
adverse to the interests of Mexican cement companies, Mexico 
will present the case to the NAFTA commission. Serra Puche 
explained that a formal request will be presented to establish 
an arbitration panel to consider the correct application of the 
U.S. antidumping law in accordance with what is established in 
Chapter 19 of NAFTA. 
  Meanwhile, Trade Negotiations Under Secretary Herminio 
Blanco 
will meet with the representatives of the affected companies to 
evaluate the possibility of a public hearing that will allow 
them to explain their arguments against the U.S. Commerce 
Department's decision. The Mexican businessmen have 30 days to 
submit comments on Friday's preliminary decision, which 
established differential margins [margenes diferenciales] of 
60.33 percent for Mexican Cement and 59.91 percent for the rest 
of the companies. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

