<F P=100> Nicaragua </F>
<H3> <TI>   Resistance Leader Against Accepting Haitians </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Resistance Leader Against Accepting Haitians </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA3105195594 Managua Radio Nicaragua Network in Spanish 30 
May 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA3105195594 </F>
<F P=104>  Managua Radio Nicaragua Network </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Six O'Clock Sharp" newscast] </F>
  [Text] Nicaraguan Resistance Vice President Jose Rivas has 
expressed his views on the Haitians refugees that the U.S. wants 
Nicaragua to accept. 
  [Begin Rivas recording] We view the plight of the Haitians 
as 
regrettable. The Nicaraguan Government's policy is strictly for 
export purposes. Here in Nicaragua we are very much aware of 
the situation we are confronting. Here in Nicaragua more than 
50 percent of the work force is unemployed. We do not believe 
it would be advisable for people from other countries, in this 
case Haiti, to come here when we cannot solve the problems of 
the Nicaraguan people. The government has implemented many 
economic plans that have not worked out. Many Nicaraguans 
cannot understand why. I believe that if we were to accept 
Haitian refugees in Nicaragua we would face situations which 
would be difficult to describe at this time. We do not believe 
Nicaragua should be a laboratory to test this type of social 
program. They are overlooking the real situation experienced by 
the Nicaraguan people. I do not believe this would be good for 
us and it worries us. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

