<H3> <TI>   Education Minister Alarcon Confirms Resignation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Education Minister Alarcon Confirms Resignation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA3005045294 Panama City LA PRENSA in Spanish 29 May 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> PA3005045294 </F>
<F P=104>  Panama City LA PRENSA </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Jose Otero] </F>
  [Text] Education Minister Marco Alarcon confirmed yesterday 
he will resign from his post to avail himself of his retirement 
as a teacher. He also said German Vergara, current Arnulfist 
Party [PA] deputy secretary general, will replace him. 
  Alarcon's resignation will be effective as of 1 July, when 
his retirement papers, currently in their final processing 
stage, are completed. It was also reported that Alarcon 
requested his vacation time, as is his right, after having been 
the education minister for three [number as published] years. 
  He took office on 1 April 1992, when he replaced Ada de 
Gordon, following President Guillermo Endara's ousting of the 
Christian Democratic Party from the government alliance. 
Alarcon denied that his separation from the post of education 
minister is due to discrepancies with the PA or with President 
Endara. 
  Meanwhile, Vergara said he accepted the appointment to the 
post. The current minister recommended him, and Endara accepted 
the recommendation. Vergara was the secretary general of the 
Health Ministry, and he acquired his teaching experience in the 
interior. 
  PA Secretary General Carlos Young Adames highly praised 
Vergara's appointment by noting he believes in the work Vergara 
will embark on despite the short term he will have heading the 
Education Ministry. 
  It was also confirmed that Bolivar Armuelles will remain 
deputy education minister until 1 September, when the government 
of President-elect Ernesto Perez Balladares begins. 

</TEXT>

