<F P=100> Panama </F>
<H3> <TI>   Canal Commission Unions Reject U.S. Proposal </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Canal Commission Unions Reject U.S. Proposal </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2705141594 Panama City LA ESTRELLA DE PANAMA in Spanish 26 
May 94 p 44 </F>

<F P=103> PA2705141594 </F>
<F P=104>  Panama City LA ESTRELLA DE PANAMA </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Esperanza Navarro Francois] </F>
  [Text] The Coalition of Panama Canal Commission's Labor 
Unions, AFL-CIO, yesterday rejected an amendment proposal 
presented to the U.S. Congress by President Bill Clinton to 
regulate Panama Canal operations administratively and 
financially, because they believe the proposal "threatens" 
worker interests. 
  According to Commission workers, the proposal gives absolute 
and total power to the Panama Canal Board of Directors by giving 
the Board authority to determine which federal standards will 
remain in effect for the Canal Commission during the transition 
period. 
  According to Commission workers, the proposal presented by 
the Panama Canal Board of Directors, based on a study and 
recommendations by the firm Arthur Anderson, "will create 
uncertainty and nervousness." The workers are afraid they will 
lose the rights they have attained with so much effort and 
sacrifice. 
  In a communique sent to the workers, the Coalition has 
alerted international organizations in the United States to 
ensure their participation in the congressional debates. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

