<F P=100> Brazil </F>
<H3> <TI>   PT Candidate Lula Warns Speculators, Pledges Reform </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    PT Candidate Lula Warns Speculators, Pledges Reform </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY0106011994 Sao Paulo AGENCIA ESTADO in Portuguese 2203 GMT 
31 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> PY0106011994 </F>
<F P=104>  Sao Paulo AGENCIA ESTADO </F>
<F P=105>  Portuguese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Brasilia, 31 May (AE) -- At a luncheon with 
entrepreneurs from Brasilia and its satellite towns, Workers 
Party [PT] presidential candidate Luiz Inacio Lula da Silva said 
that some people should fear his electoral victory. These 
people are tax evaders, speculators, corrupt people, and large 
estate owners who have unproductive land. 
  He sent a message to speculators, warning them to be 
careful. 
He promised: "Speculators will have to invest their money in 
productive areas of the economy." Lula said that the current 
problem is that the government pretends to have a fiscal policy, 
and people pretend to pay taxes. "These people cheat everybody, 
and no one thinks about Brazil." 
  The PT candidate said that the country does not need big 
laws, but big accords. "If we have clear rules, agreed upon by 
the parties involved, we will be able to establish rules that 
will allow Brazil to grow." Lula remembers that one can only 
govern by ensuring credibility among social protagonists, 
workers, entrepreneurs, and government officials. Lula promised 
to implement the country's first agrarian reform and to end 
corruption. 

</TEXT>

