<F P=100> Brazil </F>
<H3> <TI>   UK Reopens Credit Guarantees for Exports to Brazil </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    UK Reopens Credit Guarantees for Exports to Brazil </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY0106033894 Sao Paulo FOLHA DE SAO PAULO in Portuguese 27 
May 94 Section 1 p 9 </F>

<F P=103> PY0106033894 </F>
<F P=104>  Sao Paulo FOLHA DE SAO PAULO </F>
<F P=105>  Portuguese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Sergio Malbergier] </F>
  [Text] The British Government Export Credit Guarantee 
Department (ECGD) announced yesterday that it has reopened 
credit coverage of exports to Brazil, which had been suspended 
in 1983. 
  The measure was a consequence of Brazil's renegotiation of 
its foreign debt with banks and "the encouraging progress of the 
stabilization program," an ECGD communique says. 
  Michael Heseltine, secretary of state for trade and 
industry, 
said: "The resumption of the ECGD coverage of exports to Brazil 
will provide new opportunities for British companies." 
  "Brazil is the ninth largest economy in the world, and it 
will be even more open now that the effects of the debt crisis 
will begin to decrease," Heseltine said in a communique. 
  The coverage of credits was suspended in 1983 due to 
Brazil's 
delays in paying its debt. The coverage was resumed in 1989, 
but it was again suspended following new Brazilian delays with 
its debt. 
  The ECGD said that it would concentrate on covering private 
companies, particularly in areas that will encourage the 
rehabilitation of the country's economy. 
  Douglas Hurd, secretary of state for foreign and 
commonwealth 
affairs, visited Brazil at the beginning of April with a 
delegation of entrepreneurs. On that occasion he said that the 
United Kingdom wanted to increase economic relations between the 
two countries. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

