<F P=100> Brazil </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Economic Reports </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Roundup of Economic Reports </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY2705010494 </F>
<F P=103> PY2705010494 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
BFN 

    [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on economic activities monitored through 26 May. 
  The Central Bank has reported that the monetary base grew by 
a nominal 37 percent in April; 3.9 percent less than in March. 
It also reported that in April the Brazilian international net 
reserves totaled $38.3 billions while its short term reserves 
totaled $32.3 billion. During the same period, the monetary 
base grew 49 percent by the peak concept and 45 percent by the 
daily average concept. (Sao Paulo O ESTADO DE SAO PAULO in 
Portuguese 20 May 94 p B4) 
  Alexandre Loloian, Labor Ministry Employment and Salary 
Policies secretary, has reported that during the first quarter 
the national labor market registered 70,981 new jobs, of which 
48,796 were created in March -- 0.22 percent up on February. 
(Sao Paulo O ESTADO DE SAO PAULO in Portuguese 21 May 94 p B5) 
  Based on a study of the daily quotation of 1,300 products 
sold in 11 supermarket chains, Abilio Diniz, vice president of 
the Pao de Acucar supermarket chain, foresees that supermarket 
prices will have to be adjusted before the implementation of the 
real because there is a 15 to 20 percent price difference 
between sale and stock replacement prices. (Sao Paulo FOLHA DE 
SAO PAULO in Portuguese 24 May 94 S2 p 9) 
  Household appliance sales, which had increased considerably 
during the first quarter of the year, dropped by 20 percent in 
May compared with the same month last year. This led several 
companies to plan collective vacations for their employees. 
Most of the 4,000 Arno company employees will have a 5-week 
vacation as of June, the company president announced. Lourival 
Kicula, who coordinates household appliances industries, says 
all companies currently have a 15 to 30-day stock which is 
beyond the desirable stock of 5 days. (Sao Paulo FOLHA DE SAO 
PAULO in Portuguese 24 May 94 S2 p 1) 
  The Sao Paulo State Federation of Industries has reported 
that the unemployment level increased by 0.25 percent during the 
second week of May with the dismissal of 5,893 employees in Sao 
Paulo. The accumulated unemployment rate this year is 1.8 
percent or 43,800 dismissals. The accumulated unemployment rate 
for the past 12 months is 2.82 percent following the dismissal 
of 66,837 workers. Of the 46 industries studied, most workers 
were dismissed in the textile, railway equipment, paper, 
cardboard, and rubber industries. The industries with greatest 
job hirings were marble, granite, metal frames, doors, windows, 
and construction materials. (Sao Paulo GAZETA MERCANTIL in 
Portuguese 25 May 94 p 2) 
  The attempt by the Espirito Santo government to privatize 
its 
23,17 percent participation in the Espirito Santo Power Plants, 
Escelsa, through an auction at the Rio de Janeiro Stock Exchange 
on 24 May failed completely due to the lack of bidders. A new 
auction should be held next 1 or 6 June. The base price of each 
Escelsa share was quoted at $100. (Sao Paulo GAZETA MERCANTIL in 
Portuguese 25 May 94 p21) 
  The Brazilian Federation of Bank Associations today made 
public a report on the 1993 banking social balance which shows 
that the banks made a $2.9 billion profit on net assets which 
amount to $24 billion. Profits amounted to 12.3 percent of 
their assets. The dividends paid by the banks to their 
shareholders amounted to $730 million. The report shows that 
during 1993 the banks paid $22 billion in salaries to their 
674,500 employees and $2.3 billion in taxes and social 
contributions. The Brazilian banking system consists of 244 
banks with more than 31,000 branches, holding more than 47 
million savings accounts and 44 million checking accounts, 3.7 
million of which correspond to companies. The report shows that 
the average monthly volume of credit operations amounts to $95 
billion, their portfolio of financial applications and 
securities amounts to $25 billion, 80 percent of which is made 
up of government papers. (Sao Paulo AGENCIA ESTADO in Portuguese 
2021 GMT 26 May 94) 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

