  [Text] Israeli Foreign Minister Shim'on Peres has arrived. 
A very important event has taken place in his first public act: 
the Jewish-Palestine community has greeted him, which is a sign 
of new times. Peres praised Colombian democracy and said things 
are being corrected in Colombia through elections and that it is 
a privilege for him to arrive just when Colombia is voting. He 
also said Jerusalem will continue to be Israel's capital, but 
that Jerusalem will not be divided as Berlin was after World War 
II. Peres said he believes more in deeds than words regarding 
Palestinian leader Arafat's unfortunate remarks to the effect 
there would be a jihad or sacred war to liberate Palestine. 
Here is Shim'on Peres: 
  [Begin recording] [Unidentified reporter] Do you believe 
that 
results will allow your [as heard] country to continue to make 
great economic strides? 
