<H3> <TI>   Samper, Pastrana Begin Campaign for 19 Jun Runoff </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Samper, Pastrana Begin Campaign for 19 Jun Runoff </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA3105222094 Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 in Spanish 1200 GMT 31 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA3105222094 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 </F>

<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From "Caracol's 0600 to 0900" newscast] </F>
  [Text] Santa Fe de Bogota -- While the candidates who 
qualified for the 19 June runoff have started to give new life 
to their political strategies to attract popular support, the 
government and the economic groups made a vehement call on 
Colombians to analyze the proposals of the two contenders and to 
vote massively. 
  While Liberal Ernesto Samper Pizano prefers to seek 
increased 
support from his party, including its former Colombian 
presidents, Conservative Andres Pastrana Arango prefers social 
aspects such as employment and education in his government 
program. Mr. Samper Pizano said he will focus on the 
agricultural sector. He said this sector must be saved to 
ensure the peasants continue living on their plots. 
  Although the directorate of the 19 April Movement Democratic 
Alliance will decide what political course to follow this 
Thursday, in view of the electoral defeat suffered last Sunday, 
there have already been contacts with the Samper camp to reach 
some agreements. 
  The two presidential candidates will start a new and 
fast-paced race for the Presidency today. They will try to 
maintain or increase the electoral support they received on 29 
May. The two of them garnered nearly 5.2 million votes. 
  Liberal statesmen Julio Cesar Turbay Ayala and Alfonso Lopez 
Michelsen are expected to renew their support for candidate 
Samper Pizano and to urge citizens to vote. 
  Despite the optimism of the two candidates about winning a 
majority of the votes in the 19 June runoff, groups such as 
National Exporters Association and Asoexpro [expansion unknown] 
predicted a lower turnout in the runoffs due to tiresome 
abstentionism, a lack of political culture, the poor definition 
[poca identidad] of the parties, and the enthusiasm displayed by 
Colombia for the opening of the world soccer championship in the 
United States. 

</TEXT>

