<F P=100> Uruguay </F>
<H3> <TI>   Army, Uruguay To Train Military for UN Units </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Army, Uruguay To Train Military for UN Units </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY2805032394 Buenos Aires NOTICIAS ARGENTINAS in Spanish 
2247 GMT 27 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> PY2805032394 </F>
<F P=104>  Buenos Aires NOTICIAS ARGENTINAS </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Montevideo, 27 May (AFP-NA) -- Government sources 
reported that the Argentine and Uruguayan Armies agreed this 
week to maintain a "fluid exchange" between the schools in each 
country that will train Latin American officers assigned to UN 
peacekeeping forces. 
  Two colonels and two lieutenant colonels, representatives of 
the Argentine and Uruguayan Armies, concluded several days of 
meetings at Army Headquarters in Montevideo. During the 
meetings, they agreed to "cooperate between the two Armies" to 
train the future UN officers. 
  The agreement put an end to a dispute between Argentina's 
Carlos Menem and Uruguay's Luis Alberto Lacalle, who were 
disputing the seat of an eventual regional school for the Blue 
Helmets' military training. 
  The agreement includes the bilateral exchange of military 
trainers who will offer training courses to the Latin American 
Armed Forces officers assigned to UN peace missions. The 
training courses will take place in both Argentina and Uruguay. 
  The Uruguayan Armed Forces have a unit of more than 1,100 
men 
at the service of the United Nations in Mozambique, Western 
Sahara, Cambodia, Kashmir, and on the Egyptian-Israeli border, 
while Argentina has 1,200 men in UN Blue Helmet units. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

