<F P=100> Venezuela </F>
<H3> <TI>   Economic Reform Minister Resigns </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Economic Reform Minister Resigns </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA0106004994 Caracas Union Radio Network in Spanish 2200 GMT 
31 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA0106004994 </F>
<F P=104>  Caracas Union Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Union Radio News" newscast] </F>
  [Text] Asdrubal Batista, Reform of the National Economy 
minister, on the night of 30 May submitted his irrevocable 
resignation from the post he occupies, because he disagrees with 
some changes in the economic policies that are being analyzed. 
Vicente Briceno has the story: 
  [Begin Briceno recording] It seems the resignation of 
Batista, who was responsible for devising short-, mid-, and 
long-term economic strategies, is because of alleged 
disagreements with Finance Minister Julio Sosa Rodriguez, who 
has steered the economic path toward positions Batista refuses 
to accept. 
  It was known the Executive Branch will not replace Dr. 
Batista, because it is believed he achieved most of the tasks 
President Rafael Caldera assigned to him. One such task was to 
draft a report on the prospects of the Venezuelan Corporation of 
Guayana. 
  Due to this situation, the economic expert reportedly 
refused 
to attend the questioning session scheduled for 1 June at the 
National Congress. The Miraflores Palace could not confirm the 
official report on Minister Batista's resignation. However, 
unofficial spokesmen reported it as fact. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

