<F P=100> Venezuela </F>
<H3> <TI>   Caldera To Replace Investment Fund Minister </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Caldera To Replace Investment Fund Minister </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA3105202194 Caracas Union Radio Network in Spanish 2200 GMT 
29 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA3105202194 </F>
<F P=104>  Caracas Union Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Vicente Briceno from Miraflores Palace; from the </F>
"Union Radio News" newscast] 
  [Text] As we have reported, everything seems to indicate 
that President Rafael Caldera was prompted to replace Venezuelan 
Investment Fund [FIV] Minister Abdon Vivas Teran for failing to 
sell Aeropostal through the bidding process. 
  Fernando Egana, deputy minister of the Secretariat of the 
Presidency, has admitted that the chief of state has made this 
decision, because he wants to accelerate the process of 
privatization. He has added the former minister has established 
the bases for this policy and the government will develop it: 
  [Begin recording] [Egana] He has established solid and 
important bases, and the government will continue his efforts on 
such bases. 
  [Unidentified reporter] Is there anything concrete in this 
regard? 
  [Egana] A plan of privatization is already under way. 
  [Reporter] What is in store for Vivas? 
  [Egana] The president of the Republic will decide. 
  [Reporter] It was said the first attempt at privatization 
has 
failed. Will changes be made? Will a new element be introduced 
to make it more effective? 
  [Egana] Using the bases already established, the government 
will try to make greater efforts to attract foreign investments 
that are needed at this time. [end recording] 
  When asked whether the MAS [Movement Toward Socialism] will 
have a greater role in the government in view of the changes, 
Egana has said the country has achieved greater participation 
during the administration of President Caldera. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

