<F P=100> Venezuela </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Economic Developments </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Roundup of Economic Developments </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA0106003294 </F>
<F P=103> PA0106003294 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
BFN 

    [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on Venezuelan economic developments monitored through 31 
May. 
  Approximately 25,000 enterprises in Zulia State have been 
thrown into a recession because of the latest fluctuations of 
the bolivar. One business sector representative explained that 
the dollar auction mechanism is hurting Venezuelan businessmen. 
He said inflation and the lack of imported supplies are two 
short-term consequences of the instability in the exchange rate. 
He predicted there may be long-term mass layoffs and company 
closures as a result of the economic decline. (Caracas Union 
Radio Network in Spanish 0200 GMT 22 May 94) 
  Energy and Mines Minister Erwin Jose Arrieta has announced 
Venezuela will obtain an additional $120 million as a result of 
higher prices on the international oil market. He explained that 
higher oil prices resulted in $70 million in additional revenues 
last month. Arrieta attributed the increase in oil prices to 
temporary conditions, such as repairs in North Sea oil 
facilities, Nigeria's domestic situation, the conflict in Yemen, 
and increased consumption by industrialized nations. (Caracas 
Union Radio Network in Spanish 2200 GMT 26 May 94) 
  Venezuelan exports to Andean Group countries increased by 
40.6 percent in the first quarter of the year, going from $195 
million in the first quarter of 1993 to $275 million in 1994, 
according to estimates by the Cartagena Agreement Board. 
According to the figures, Venezuela replaced Colombia as the 
largest exporter in interregional trade. The estimated value of 
interregional trade amounted to $698 million. (Caracas EL 
NACIONAL in Spanish 27 May 94 p E-7) 

</TEXT>

