<F P=100> CARIBBEAN </F>
<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   Authorities To Respect Asylum Seekers' Rights </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Authorities To Respect Asylum Seekers' Rights </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA3105153094 Mexico City NOTIMEX in Spanish 1442 GMT 31 May 
94 </F>

<F P=103> PA3105153094 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City NOTIMEX </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Brussels, 31 May (NOTIMEX) -- Cuba has sent to the 
Belgian authorities a written commitment to respect the human 
rights of the 113 Cubans who invaded that country's diplomatic 
headquarters in Havana. The two parties agreed that there should 
be a peaceful evacuation. 
  The Belgian Foreign Ministry, through its spokesman, told 
NOTIMEX that it had received a message from Cuban authorities 
committing themselves to not persecuting asylum seekers after 
they leave the embassy. Belgium made it clear it had no 
intention of receiving [recibir] the Cubans and called for a 
"swift and humane" solution to the problem that would restore 
tranquillity to the diplomatic headquarters in Havana, which is 
made up of five officials. 
  One of the 114 refugees voluntarily left the Belgian 
diplomatic headquarters on Sunday evening and the police did not 
ask him to produce identification, the Spanish newspaper EL PAIS 
reported today. 
  The spokesman said Belgium will continue giving humanitarian 
aid to the asylum seekers, including 34 women and 24 children. 
Belgian authorities sent additional drinks and food to the Cuban 
refugees in the embassy. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-33058 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drlat105_a_94002" </HT>


