<F P=100> CARIBBEAN </F>
<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   Matanzas PCC Reports on Self-Employment Violations </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Matanzas PCC Reports on Self-Employment Violations </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   FL0106221394 Havana Radio Rebelde Network in Spanish 0900 
GMT 1 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL0106221394 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana Radio Rebelde Network </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The provincial plenum of the Communist Party of Cuba 
in Matanzas analyzed, as a special point on the agenda, the 
current situation in the province regarding implementation of 
the measures recently approved by the Council of State as well 
as Decree-Law 186, which regulates self-employment violations. 
Osvaldo Umpierrez, president of the Administration Council in 
the province, advised that there are currently 10,227 people 
self-employed, mostly as hairdressers, manicurists, and 
transport cart drivers. 
  Since February when Decree-Law 186 was approved, a 
contingent 
of 231 tax inspectors have imposed over 400 fines, of which more 
than half are against violators from other provinces. Also under 
review is the situation of over 500 automobiles that are not in 
the possession of their owners, 52 of which have been 
confiscated. Additionally, 1,300 motorcycles have been 
inventoried. Currently, in the province, 47 cases of money 
hoarding are being worked on, six of which are now being 
analyzed by the commission created for this purpose. 

</TEXT>

